17/11/2006
PODGORICA, Montenegro -- The presidents of Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia, Serbia and Montenegro signed an agreement Thursday (November 16th) to develop closer co-operation in the fight against crime and terrorism.
Croatia's Stipe Mesic, Montenegro's Filip Vujanovic, and Nebojsa Radmanovic of Bosnia and Herzegovina met in the Montenegrin coastal town of Przno.
Serbian President Boris Tadic did not attend the meeting but sent a signed copy of the agreement.
The four leaders issued a statement pledging to work together to "suppress organised crime and terrorism" and to "strengthen national judiciaries in line with EU standards".
(AP - 16/11/06)
